The Council of Graduate Schools (CGS)/ National Science Foundation (NSF) Dean in Residence project was designed to deepen the conversation between NSF &ndash; a major funder of graduate students and graduate initiatives &ndash; and the campus leaders responsible for ensuring access to and success in high quality master?s and doctoral degree programs. 

These objectives were met through a variety of activities, including:

a series of conference presentations by NSF program officers at annual CGS and regional affiliate meetings;
a compilation of a set of resources universities use to actively assist graduate students and prospective graduate students as they apply for NSF?s prestigious Graduate Research Fellowship Program (GRFP);
the development of a speaker series that brought graduate education researchers and experts to NSF to give presentations to the Division of Graduate Education and other NSF staff;
the facilitation of in-depth discussions between NSF and other federal agencies that value investment in graduate education, as well as  between the various NSF directorates; and
a hosted workshop, engaging funders and graduate educators from the U.S., Canada, Germany, Japan, and the European Union in a discussion of strategies for evaluating the impact of international experiences on the subsequent careers of STEM doctoral students. 


All panels and presentations were coordinated by the dean in residence, who split time between CGS and NSF, and the process for ensuring continuing participation in national and regional graduate education conferences has become more regularized.  Results of the workshop on international research experiences have been disseminated widely online and through a webinar attended by approximately 250 graduate faculty and administrators.  Results of the CGS/NSF dean in residence project have also appeared as lead articles in the CGS newsletter.  Through conference presentations, facilitated dialogue, webinars, research and analysis, this project has helped NSF to understand the impact of the investments they are making in graduate education and to gain the insights about day-to-day operations on university campuses and in STEM degree programs that can further refine and strengthen their investment portfolio.



